ation fueled efforts to ensure that management would share the fruits of progress with workers, consumers, and society as a whole. Focusing on wage and price determination in steel, automobiles, and electrical equipment, Milner reveals how the management of concentrated industries understood its ability to distribute income to its stakeholders as well as why economists, courts, and public policymakers struggled to curtail the exercise of that market power at its source.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCorporate profits-United States. 0aPrices-United States. 0aWages-United States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300262940?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262940/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles